<p class="lead"><strong>Headers and footers are areas in a document at the top and bottom margin areas used for information or elements in the document that will appear on many pages or even all pages.</strong></p class="lead"> 

<p>Common uses for headers and footers are for document
titles, page numbers, dates, author name, company name, file path, etc.</p>

<p>You can control the placement of the header or footer within the margin. The
information you place in a header or footer will print for all pages in that
document or a section of the document.</p>

<p>You can change the type style, font size, justification, etc. for the text
that you place in the header or footer.</p>

<p>You can switch between the header and footer by pressing in the icon shown.
You can insert the page number function by clicking on the first icon. This
will automatically calculate the page number. The fourth icon lets you insert a
date, and the fifth icon lets you insert the time. Headers and footers will
only show under the Print Layout View.</p>

<p>You do not have to use both the header and the footer. You can choose to use
only a header or only a footer; you can choose to use both or choose none at
all.</p>


<p>Accessing Headers and Footers is a little different based on your version of word processor.</p>

